[{"_1":2},"routes/puzzle-detail",{"_3":4},"data",{"_5":6,"_7":8,"_9":10},"status","success","slug","watermelons-drying-in-the-sun","puzzle",{"_7":8,"_11":12,"_37":38,"_39":40,"_41":42,"_43":44},"metadata",{"_13":14,"_15":16,"_17":18,"_19":22,"_24":25,"_27":28,"_29":30,"_31":30,"_32":33,"_34":35,"_36":35},"id","puzzle-13","title","Watermelons Drying in The Sun","difficulty",{"_19":20,"_21":20},"concepts","easy","reasoning",[23],"algebra","tags",[26],"has-solution","credit","Classic puzzle known as the \"Potato Paradox\" or \"Watermelon Paradox.\" Question and solution written by Puzzlestone Peak.","dateCreated","2025-11-02","lastUpdated","changelog","2025-11-03: Added to Puzzlestone Peak","preview","A farmer is proud of his newest feat: growing a 120 kg watermelon that he wants to enter in the farming contest next week. Using a special sensor, he detects...","websitePreview","content","<p>A farmer is proud of his newest feat: growing a 120 kg watermelon that he wants to enter in the farming contest next week. Using a special sensor, he detects that the watermelon is 99% water by mass.</p>\n<p>However, one day the wind blows off the tarp sheltering the watermelon, leaving it out in the sun to shrivel up and lose some of its water content. The farmer is devastated.</p>\n<p>“The watermelon is ruined! I can’t enter it in the contest!”</p>\n<p>“Why not?” his wife replies.</p>\n<p>The farmer uses the sensor. “You see? It’s only 98% water now.”</p>\n<p>“That’s still pretty heavy.”</p>\n<p>“You don’t understand. Mr. Jones next door has a 100 kg watermelon. This won’t do at all.”</p>\n<p>How heavy is the farmer’s watermelon now?</p>\n<details class=\"content-block solution-block\" data-type=\"solution\"><summary class=\"solution-label\">Solution</summary><div class=\"solution-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p>The watermelon is only 60 kg heavy now.</p><p>At the start, the watermelon consists of 99% of water by mass. This means that the non-water parts of the watermelon is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi>%</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>120</mn><mtext> kg</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1.2</mn><mtext> kg</mtext></mrow><annotation>1\\% \\times 120 \\text{ kg} = 1.2 \\text{ kg}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1%</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">120</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> kg</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1.2</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> kg</span></span></span></span></span>.</p><p>After losing some of its water content, the 1.2 kg is now 2% of the watermelon’s weight, which works out to only 60 kg for watermelon’s full weight.</p></div></details>","rawContent","\nA farmer is proud of his newest feat: growing a 120 kg watermelon that he wants to enter in the farming contest next week. Using a special sensor, he detects that the watermelon is 99% water by mass.\n\nHowever, one day the wind blows off the tarp sheltering the watermelon, leaving it out in the sun to shrivel up and lose some of its water content. The farmer is devastated.\n\n“The watermelon is ruined! I can’t enter it in the contest!”\n\n“Why not?” his wife replies.\n\nThe farmer uses the sensor. “You see? It’s only 98% water now.”\n\n“That’s still pretty heavy.”\n\n“You don’t understand. Mr. Jones next door has a 100 kg watermelon. This won’t do at all.”\n\nHow heavy is the farmer’s watermelon now?\n\n:::solution\nThe watermelon is only 60 kg heavy now.\n\nAt the start, the watermelon consists of 99% of water by mass. This means that the non-water parts of the watermelon is $1\\% \\times 120 \\text{ kg} = 1.2 \\text{ kg}$.\n\nAfter losing some of its water content, the 1.2 kg is now 2% of the watermelon’s weight, which works out to only 60 kg for watermelon’s full weight.\n:::\n","dynamicBlocks",[],"inlineComponents",{}]
